SECURITIES INDUSTRY ESSENTIALS LICENSE EXAM MANUAL
A comprehensive study guide and textbook designed for preparing for the Securities Industry Essentials (SIE) exam, covering topics like capital markets, securities, and regulatory frameworks.
0.entity_name: SECURITIES INDUSTRY ESSENTIALS LICENSE EXAM MANUAL

1.content:
Kaplan North America, LLC
The publishing company responsible for creating and distributing the Securities Industry Essentials License Exam Manual, including educational resources and study materials.

2.content:
FINRA
The Financial Industry Regulatory Authority that administers the SIE exam and regulates securities industry practices in the United States.

3.content:
SIE
The Securities Industry Essentials exam, a qualifying examination required for individuals seeking to work as representative-level registrants in the securities industry.

4.content:
Prometric Testing Centers
Third-party testing centers that proctor FINRA-administered exams including the SIE exam.

5.content:
Federal Reserve
The central banking system of the United States responsible for monetary policy and economic regulation, mentioned in relation to economic theories and market impacts.

6.content:
SEC
The Securities and Exchange Commission, a federal agency that regulates the securities industry and enforces securities laws.

7.content:
World Athletics Championship
A global sports competition featuring top athletes in track and field events, mentioned as an example of an event in the text but not directly related to securities content.

8.content:
Tokyo
The host city of the World Athletics Championship, mentioned as an example of a location in the text but not directly related to securities content.

9.content:
Noah Carter
A sprinter who set a new 100m sprint record at the World Athletics Championship, mentioned as an example in the text but not directly related to securities content.

10.content:
100m Sprint Record
A benchmark in athletics representing the fastest time recorded for the 100-meter sprint, referenced in a sports context but not directly tied to securities.

11.content:
Carbon-Fiber Spikes
Advanced sprinting shoes used in athletics that provide enhanced speed and traction, mentioned as an example in the text but not directly related to securities content.

12.content:
World Athletics Federation
The governing body overseeing the World Athletics Championship and record validations, mentioned as an example in the text but not directly related to securities content.

13.content:
Investment Company Act of 1940
A federal law regulating investment companies, covered in Unit 4 of the Securities Industry Essentials manual.

14.content:
Federal Reserve Policy Announcement
An anticipated policy decision by the Federal Reserve that could influence investor confidence and market stability, mentioned as a regulatory issue.

15.content:
Central Registration Depository
The system through which FINRA member firms apply for and pay fees to register individuals for FINRA-administered exams like the SIE.

16.content:
Web CRD
The online system used by FINRA for managing registration information, including exam history and firm affiliations.

17.content:
CRD
The Central Registration Depository system used by FINRA for managing registration information, also known as Web CRD.

18.content:
Qualified Institutional Buyers
Institutional investors who own and invest a minimum of $100 million in securities on a discretionary basis, mentioned in the context of primary market participants.<SEP>Institutional investors who own and invest a minimum of $100 million in securities on a discretionary basis.

19.content:
SecuritiesPro TM QBank
An exam preparation tool included in Kaplan's study package that provides practice questions similar in style and content to the actual SIE exam.

20.content:
Checkpoint Exams
Fixed exams administered after each unit of the course to check student progress before advancing to the next unit.

21.content:
Midterm Exam
A fixed exam administered approximately at the midpoint of the course to assess overall progress.

22.content:
Practice Exam
A fixed exam designed to closely replicate the true exam experience for practice purposes.

23.content:
Mastery Exam
A fixed exam designed to closely replicate the true exam experience, typically taken close to the actual exam date.

24.content:
Performance Tracker
A tool used to identify areas of weakness after completing practice and mastery exams, allowing for targeted study.

25.content:
Video Library
A collection of short, engaging videos covering key topics in the securities industry curriculum.

26.content:
Exam Tips and Content Updates
Informational resources on the Kaplan dashboard providing updates about rule and regulation changes for the exam.

27.content:
Corrections Link
A resource on the Kaplan dashboard that provides information about corrections to errors in the text.

28.content:
Test Topic Alert
Features in the manual that highlight content especially likely to appear on the exam.

29.content:
Take Note
Special information sections in the manual designed to amplify important points.

30.content:
Example
Practical applications of theory presented in the manual as quick, interactive, real-world illustrations.

31.content:
Practice Question
Questions within each learning objective designed to help students see how topics might be presented on the exam.

32.content:
Knowledge Check
Short tests after each lesson to measure comprehension and reinforce essential material covered in that lesson.

33.content:
Study Calendar
A customizable tool on the Kaplan dashboard that helps students plan their use of study materials and tools.

34.content:
Primary Markets
Markets where securities are sold by issuers to raise capital, contrasting with secondary markets where securities trade between investors.

35.content:
Secondary Markets
Markets where securities trade between investors after their initial issuance in primary markets.

36.content:
Initial Public Offering
The first time an issuer distributes securities to the public, also known as an IPO.

37.content:
Additional Public Offering
A subsequent offering of securities by a company after its initial public offering, also called APO or follow-on offering.

38.content:
Underwriting Commitments
Agreements between underwriters and issuers that define the level of commitment required from underwriters in securities offerings.

39.content:
Best Efforts Underwriting
An underwriting arrangement where underwriters act as agents and are not committed to purchasing unsold shares, with funds held in escrow.

40.content:
Firm Commitment Underwriting
An underwriting contract where underwriters commit to purchasing securities from the issuer at a specified price, acting as principals.

41.content:
Syndicates
Groups of broker-dealers that form joint ventures to facilitate large capital-raising processes in underwriting.

42.content:
Selling Group
Members of a syndicate who assist in selling securities but do not commit capital or hold inventory, unlike syndicate members.

43.content:
Managing Underwriter
A member of a syndicate who takes on a lead role and provides significant resources to the venture.

44.content:
Institutional Investors
Entities that pool money to purchase securities and other investment assets, including banks, insurance companies, pension funds, hedge funds, and mutual funds.<SEP>Institutional investors are entities that invest large sums of money and have higher communication and disclosure expectations compared to retail investors.

45.content:
Retail Investors
Individual investors who invest their own assets, typically less knowledgeable than institutional investors with higher disclosure expectations.<SEP>Individual investors who invest their own assets, typically less knowledgeable than institutional investors.<SEP>Retail investors are individual investors who typically have lower sophistication levels and require more protection in investment transactions.

46.content:
Accredited Investors
Accredited investors are a subset of investors that include institutional investors and certain qualified retail investors with specific financial criteria or professional credentials.<SEP>Individuals or entities who meet specific financial criteria to qualify for special investor protections and privileges.<SEP>Investors who meet certain financial criteria, including those who qualify as institutional investors and certain retail investors with specific income or asset thresholds.

47.content:
Insiders of Security Issuer
Officers, board members, and major stockholders of a security's issuer who qualify as accredited investors.

48.content:
Government-Issued Bonds
Debt securities issued by the federal government or its agencies, including Treasury bonds and agency debt.

49.content:
Municipal Bonds
Debt securities issued by municipalities such as counties and cities for funding infrastructure projects.

50.content:
Corporate Bonds
Debt securities issued by corporations to raise capital, mentioned in the context of debt securities.

51.content:
Equity Securities
Securities representing ownership in a company, including common stocks and preferred stocks.

52.content:
Common Stocks
Equity securities that represent ownership in a corporation with voting rights and potential for dividends.

53.content:
Preferred Stock
Equity securities that have characteristics of both common stock and bonds, typically paying fixed dividends.

54.content:
ADRs
American Depositary Receipts, representing foreign company shares traded in U.S. markets.

55.content:
Options
Derivative securities that give the holder the right, but not the obligation, to buy or sell an underlying asset at a specified price.

56.content:
Municipal Fund Securities
Securities related to municipal investment funds, including municipal bonds and other debt instruments.

57.content:
Partnerships
Investment vehicles that are pass-through entities for tax purposes, mentioned in the context of other investment vehicles.

58.content:
REITs
Real Estate Investment Trusts that own and operate income-generating real estate properties.

59.content:
ETFs
Exchange-Traded Funds that trade like stocks on exchanges but hold diversified portfolios of assets.

60.content:
ETNs
Exchange-Traded Notes, debt securities issued by financial institutions that track indices or other benchmarks.

61.content:
Life Insurance-Based Products
Insurance products that combine life insurance with investment components, covered in Unit 4 of the manual.

62.content:
Investment Company
A company that pools money from investors to invest in securities, regulated under the Investment Company Act of 1940.

63.content:
Customer Accounts
Accounts maintained by broker-dealers for their clients, including nonqualified and qualified accounts.

64.content:
Nonqualified Accounts
Customer accounts that do not meet the requirements for qualified retirement accounts.

65.content:
Qualified Accounts
Customer accounts that meet specific requirements for tax-advantaged retirement accounts.

66.content:
Account Features
Characteristics and capabilities of customer accounts including margin features and other account-specific attributes.

67.content:
Investment Risks
Potential losses or adverse outcomes associated with different types of investments, covered in Unit 7.

68.content:
Making Recommendations
Process of providing investment advice to clients based on their needs and risk tolerance, covered in Unit 7.

69.content:
Taxation
The impact of taxes on investment returns and the methods for calculating tax implications of securities transactions.

70.content:
Calculating Yields and Returns
Methods for determining the income and performance of investments, covered in Unit 8.

71.content:
Business Cycle
The periodic fluctuations in economic activity including expansion, peak, contraction, and trough phases.

72.content:
Economic Theories
Conceptual frameworks explaining how economies function, including theories about monetary and fiscal policy.

73.content:
Government Regulators
Regulatory bodies that oversee financial markets, including SEC and other government agencies.

74.content:
Self-Regulatory Organizations
Industry groups that regulate their own members and maintain standards for securities industry practices.

75.content:
Anti-Money Laundering
Regulatory framework designed to prevent the use of financial systems for money laundering activities.

76.content:
Bank Secrecy Act
Federal law requiring financial institutions to maintain records and report suspicious transactions to prevent money laundering.

77.content:
Market Manipulation
Unlawful practices that distort the price or supply of securities in the market.

78.content:
Insider Trading
The illegal trading of securities based on material non-public information.

79.content:
Prohibited Activities
Activities that are forbidden under securities regulations and industry rules.

80.content:
Communications With the Public
Regulations governing how financial professionals communicate with investors and the public about securities.

81.content:
Registered Representatives
Individuals who have passed required exams and are registered with FINRA to conduct securities business.

82.content:
Member Firm
A brokerage firm that is a member of FINRA and subject to its regulations.

83.content:
Broker-Dealers
Financial institutions that engage in buying and selling securities for their own account or on behalf of customers.

84.content:
Investment Bankers
Financial professionals who help companies issue securities and facilitate capital raising activities.

85.content:
Underwriters
Broker-dealers who work with issuers to bring securities to the market and sell them to investors.<SEP>Underwriters are investment banks or broker-dealers who assist issuers in preparing registration statements and prospectuses, and help distribute securities in the primary market.

86.content:
Issuers
Entities that create and offer securities to raise capital, including corporations, municipalities, and government agencies.

87.content:
Investors
Individuals or entities who purchase securities in the primary market with intent to hold them for investment purposes.

88.content:
Securities Industry Essentials
The title of the comprehensive study guide for preparing for the SIE exam, covering all major topics in securities industry fundamentals.

89.content:
Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC)
The SEC is the primary federal regulator in the securities industry responsible for overseeing securities markets and enforcing securities laws.

90.content:
Securities Act of 1933
The Securities Act of 1933 is a federal law designed to ensure investors are fully informed about securities and their issuing companies during primary market transactions.

91.content:
Municipal Advisors
Municipal advisors are investment bankers who advise municipalities on issuing municipal debt and other municipal securities, but cannot serve as underwriters for the same issues.

92.content:
Registration Statement (S-1)
The registration statement is a document filed with the SEC that discloses material information about a security issue before it can be sold in the primary market.

93.content:
Cooling-Off Period
The cooling-off period is a minimum 20-day window after filing a registration statement during which no sales solicitations are allowed but certain advertising activities may occur.

94.content:
Tombstone Advertisement
A tombstone advertisement is a minimal announcement permitted during the cooling-off period that provides basic information about a new securities offering.

95.content:
Preliminary Prospectus (Red Herring)
A preliminary prospectus or red herring is used to gauge investor interest and gather indications of interest before final pricing occurs.

96.content:
Indication of Interest
An indication of interest is a nonbinding declaration by investors expressing potential interest in purchasing securities after the registration becomes effective.

97.content:
Due Diligence
Due diligence refers to the process where underwriters examine securities to determine suitability for specific customers and conduct formal presentations to representatives.

98.content:
Blue-Sky Filings
Blue-sky filings refer to state-level securities registrations that must be coordinated with federal registration processes for securities offerings.

99.content:
Effective Date
The effective date is when the SEC allows a security to be offered to investors, marking the end of the cooling-off period and beginning of sales.

100.content:
Broker-Dealers (BDs)
Broker-dealers are financial institutions that act as intermediaries between issuers and investors in securities transactions.

101.content:
Issuer
An issuer is a company or organization that creates and sells securities to raise capital in the primary market.

102.content:
Primary Market
The primary market is where new securities are issued and sold directly by the issuer to investors for the first time.

103.content:
Secondary Market
The secondary market is where previously issued securities are traded between investors after their initial offering in the primary market.

104.content:
Insiders of Security's Issuer
Insiders of a security's issuer include officers, board members, and major stockholders who qualify as accredited investors.

105.content:
Series 7 License
The Series 7 license is a professional credential that qualifies individuals to sell securities in the primary market.

106.content:
Series 65 License
The Series 65 license is a professional credential that qualifies individuals to provide investment advice and conduct securities transactions.

107.content:
Series 82 License
The Series 82 license is a professional credential that qualifies individuals to act as municipal advisors.

108.content:
Rule 501 of Regulation D
Rule 501 of Regulation D establishes the criteria for determining who qualifies as an accredited investor under the Securities Act of 1933.

109.content:
Municipal Debt
Municipal debt refers to bonds and other securities issued by municipalities to raise capital for public projects.

110.content:
Municipal Securities
Municipal securities include bonds, notes, and other debt instruments issued by municipalities.
